Comprehen- sion, he said, was for few 3 apprehension was for every man who had hands and a head to rule them, and an eye to direct them. Out of this arose one of his de- ficiencies. He could go largely into the generalities of a subject, and relished greatly others doing it, so that they did do it really and well3 but he was averse to abstract and wide reasonings.
